SIMPLE: wigwam
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wigwam
<hw>Wig"wam</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the Algonquin or
Massachusetts Indian word <ets>w⟦emac⟧k</ets>, ⟦ldquo⟧his house,⟦rdquo⟧
or ⟦ldquo⟧dwelling place;⟦rdquo⟧ with possessive and locative affixes,
<ets>w⟦emac⟧-kou-om-ut</ets>, ⟦ldquo⟧in his (or their) house,⟦rdquo⟧
contracted by the English to <ets>weekwam</ets>, and
<ets>wigwam</ets>.]</ety> <def>An Indian cabin or hut, usually of a
conical form, and made of a framework of poles covered with hides, bark,
or mats; -- called also <altname>tepee</altname>.</def>
<altsp>[Sometimes written also <asp>weekwam</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Very spacious was the <qex>wigwam</qex>,⟦br⟧
Made of deerskin dressed and whitened,⟦br⟧
With the gods of the Dacotahs⟦br⟧
Drawn and painted on its curtains.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>wigwam</xex>, or Indian house, of a
circular or oval shape, was made of bark or mats laid over a framework
of branches of trees stuck in the ground in such a manner as to converge
at the top, where was a central aperture for the escape of smoke from
the fire beneath. The better sort had also a lining of mats. For
entrance and egress, two low openings were left on opposite sides, one
or the other of which was closed with bark or mats, according to the
direction of the wind.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Palfrey.</au></rj> </note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wike</ent>⟦br⟧
